<paragraph blockId="2.[151,388,582,608]" box="[151,388,582,608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,388,582,608]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,388,582,608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[207,290,582,608]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Atlides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,290,582,608]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Atlides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Section
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,653,966]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">
Six synapomorphies characterize the 
<taxonomicName box="[572,650,653,678]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Atlides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[572,650,653,678]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Atlides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Section in the phylogenetic results (
<tableCitation box="[1062,1148,653,678]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,1013,1036]" captionText="TABLE 1. List of synapomorphies from the phylogenetic analysis of the Atlides Section (Martins et al. 2018)." pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Table 1</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1162,1230,653,678]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionText="FIGURE 8. Cladogram modified from Martins et al. (2018)." pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), including a cleft anal angle of the hindwing (
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, A. R. P. &amp; Duarte, M. &amp; Robbins, R. K." box="[462,680,689,714]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref9760" refString="Martins, A. R. P., Duarte, M. &amp; Robbins, R. K. (2018) Evolution of male secondary sexual organs in hairstreak butterflies (Lepidoptera, Lycaenidae). Cladistics, 1 - 25." type="book chapter" year="2018">
Martins 
<emphasis box="[557,613,689,714]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). This trait was used historically to characterize the group (
<bibRefCitation author="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O." pageId="2" pageNumber="121" refId="ref9506" refString="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (1887 - 1901) Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Lepidoptera-Rhopalocera. Fam. Lycaenidae. London, Dulau &amp; Co., Bernard Quaritch, 2, 112 pp." type="book" year="1887">
Godman &amp; Salvin 
<date box="[262,320,726,750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" value="1887" valueMax="1901">1887</date>
</bibRefCitation>
–1901; 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins, R. K." box="[405,581,725,750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" refId="ref9921" refString="Robbins, R. K. (2004 a) Introduction to the checklist of Eumaeini (Lycaenidae). In: Lamas, G. (Ed.), Checklist: Part 4 A. Hesperioidea - Papilionoidea. In: Heppner, J. B. (Ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera. Folume 5 A. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera, Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, pp. xxiv-xxx." type="book" year="2004">Robbins 2004a</bibRefCitation>
). It occurs in all species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[951,1029,725,750]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Atlides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[951,1029,725,750]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Atlides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Section (illustrated for each genus, 
<figureCitation box="[151,273,761,786]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1027,1049]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,412,991]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1437,397,1006]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–15. Hindwing anal lobe cleft (black arrows). 9. Arcas imperialis, 10. Brangas getus, 11. Atlides cosa (with a forewing double scent pad in the discal cell—red arrow), 12. Theritas drucei, 13. Lucilda danaus, 14. Pseudolycaena damo, 15. Denivia silma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Figs. 9–15</figureCitation>
). The cleft anal angle occurs at vein 2A, which usually terminates on the distal side of the indentation. Indentations are unreported in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.Doubleday" authorityYear="1847" box="[574,685,797,822]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Eumaeini">Eumaeini</taxonomicName>
, except for two species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1001,1127,797,822]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Panthiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1001,1127,797,822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Panthiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O." box="[1144,1421,797,822]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" refId="ref9506" refString="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (1887 - 1901) Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Lepidoptera-Rhopalocera. Fam. Lycaenidae. London, Dulau &amp; Co., Bernard Quaritch, 2, 112 pp." type="book" year="1887">
Godman &amp; Salvin 
<date box="[1366,1421,798,822]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" value="1887" valueMax="1901">1887</date>
</bibRefCitation>
– 1901). The depth of the cleft anal angle was treated as three states in the phylogenetic analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, A. R. P. &amp; Duarte, M. &amp; Robbins, R. K." box="[1214,1425,833,858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref9760" refString="Martins, A. R. P., Duarte, M. &amp; Robbins, R. K. (2018) Evolution of male secondary sexual organs in hairstreak butterflies (Lepidoptera, Lycaenidae). Cladistics, 1 - 25." type="book chapter" year="2018">
Martins 
<emphasis box="[1309,1356,834,857]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">et a.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O." box="[301,586,869,894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" refId="ref9506" refString="Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (1887 - 1901) Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Lepidoptera-Rhopalocera. Fam. Lycaenidae. London, Dulau &amp; Co., Bernard Quaritch, 2, 112 pp." type="book" year="1887">
Godman &amp; Salvin (
<date box="[528,586,870,894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" value="1887" valueMax="1901">1887</date>
</bibRefCitation>
–1901), a deep indentation occurs in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1832" box="[1014,1078,870,893]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Arcas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1078,870,893]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Arcas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1096,1167,869,894]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1027,1049]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,412,991]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1437,397,1006]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–15. Hindwing anal lobe cleft (black arrows). 9. Arcas imperialis, 10. Brangas getus, 11. Atlides cosa (with a forewing double scent pad in the discal cell—red arrow), 12. Theritas drucei, 13. Lucilda danaus, 14. Pseudolycaena damo, 15. Denivia silma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), a shallow indentation occurs in 
<taxonomicName box="[260,355,906,929]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Brangas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[260,355,906,929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Brangas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[371,465,905,930]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1027,1049]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,412,991]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1437,397,1006]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–15. Hindwing anal lobe cleft (black arrows). 9. Arcas imperialis, 10. Brangas getus, 11. Atlides cosa (with a forewing double scent pad in the discal cell—red arrow), 12. Theritas drucei, 13. Lucilda danaus, 14. Pseudolycaena damo, 15. Denivia silma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Figs. 10</figureCitation>
), and an “intermediate” indentation occurs in all other members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1267,1345,905,930]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Atlides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1267,1345,905,930]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Atlides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Section (
<figureCitation box="[159,295,941,966]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1027,1049]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,412,991]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1437,397,1006]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–15. Hindwing anal lobe cleft (black arrows). 9. Arcas imperialis, 10. Brangas getus, 11. Atlides cosa (with a forewing double scent pad in the discal cell—red arrow), 12. Theritas drucei, 13. Lucilda danaus, 14. Pseudolycaena damo, 15. Denivia silma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="121">Figs. 11–15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
